nce is no longer valid.  The offence for driving without a licence is set out in section 38 of the Road Traffic Act 1961.\n\nTo drive a vehicle, a driver with an identified or specified illness must meet strict medical standards, which are assessed by the person’s doctor. Medical checks are required to ensure a person’s fitness to drive for road safety reasons.  A medical report must be completed by a general practitioner (GP) and a licence may be issued for one, three or ten years.\n\nAn Garda Síochána have access to data on the National Vehicle Driver File (NVDF) as part of their Mobility Strategy and therefore can detect and prosecute a driver who continues to drive while disqualified. This is the case whether or not a licence has been surrendered.  It should be noted that for disqualifications issued in 2024, the licence holder is given 14 days in which to surrender the licence/permit from commencement of the disqualification.\n\n While it is an offence not to possess a TV licence, prosecution through the courts is a last resort. Details of prosecutions are not under my remit and my Department does not hold the requested figures. Timing of court hearings and details of prosecutions and sentencing are a matter for the Courts Service.", :token-overlap-p-by-sentence [0.46153846153846156], :answer "Under section 38 of the Road Traffic Act 1961, a person caught driving without a valid driving licence is liable on summary conviction to:  \n• a fine of up to €5,000, or  \n• imprisonment for up to six months, or  \n• both a fine and imprisonment.", :cosine-similarity 0.8402988216877483, :bleu-faithfulness 0.004037803351689306, :rouge-l-f1 0.42307691855029594} {:metric-llm-faithfulness-explanation "{\n  \"reasoning\": \"Each element of the statement directly mirrors the context: there are no current plans for further fare reductions; Budget 2024 funding continues the 20% PSO fare cut, extends the Young Adult Card (50% off) to 24–25‑year‑olds on PSO and commercial service